<p class="article-lead">Perfume bottle decoration should be selected by material, artwork, quantity and durability—not from a rendering alone.</p><p>Screen printing offers direct color and clean branding but has registration and color tolerances. Hot stamping adds metallic detail within suitable areas. Coating changes the whole glass appearance; gradients and opaque colors need physical approval. Frosting creates texture, while labels provide flexibility for short runs and detailed information.</p><h2>Plan process combinations carefully</h2><p>Every added operation creates handling, alignment and reject risk. Confirm decoration order, printable area, adhesion and resistance to rubbing or fragrance contact. Keep a signed physical sample and define acceptable variation under agreed lighting.</p><p>Artwork should use the decorator's dieline and process limits. Fine lines, tiny reversed text and colors crossing sharp curves may not reproduce like a screen design.</p>
